Rather than upload a series of clips, I have prepared a compilation of the sounds produced by Pied Wagtails [subspecies Motacilla alba yarrellii] as they settled into a roost. The location was a stand of four deciduous trees (around 8m in height) in a car park at a shopping mall. For at least the last two winters, up to 140 Pied Wagtails have used the trees until, sometime in late October, the foliage begins to fall and the birds move away (I do not know where they go). The edited clip splits into three roughly equal parts, each about 20 seconds long. In the first section, some birds have arrived and are calling (mainly) from the ground before flying up among the foliage. In the second clip, most have now arrived and many are calling in a kind of animated chorus (whilst I say 'many', I could not see any more than a handful of birds, most of which were now hidden). The third clip [begins at 0:48] is the most interesting. In it, you can hear the 'white noise' created by a number of birds bill-snapping. Once again, I do not know how many birds are doing this. Furthermore, I could not see any birds well enough to even observe the action. By then, it was dark. The bill snapping, in my estimation, is an expression of one bird effectively asserting proprietorial rights to its roosting perch. Once all the birds had settled down, the bill snapping ceased, although occasional calls still punctuated the air. The bill snapping is a curious sound. It suggests static or hailstones. You need to listen closely to hear it, even though it was coming like a crackling wave from every tree in the roost. It was as though most birds were contributing to the broadcast, not just a few. In the third clip bill snapping occurs constantly. It is best heard after a passing Herring Gull [1:20] causes a bit of a lull in 'ordinary' chirping among the wagtails; in the brief absence of chirps, you can heard the bill snapping fairly clearly, for example at 1:25 or at 1:40. Among the range of vocalisations produced by the wagtails, another aggressive-sounding call is quite like the hiss of a Goldfinch threatening another Goldfinch at, for example, a feeder. The Pied Wagtail equivalent is at 1:12 and 1:17.  Bill snapping by Pied wagtails is mentioned in THE BIRDS OF THE WESTERN PALEARCTIC in vol. five, page 645. David W Emley also published a useful note on the subject in British Birds vol. 78 (1985), page 110.

loc: Bath, Bath and North East Somerset, England
rmk:
Recording of approx 200 Pied Wagtails as their come to their roost in the evening. 

As the sun sets, the wagtails come to the centre of Bath and fly together from rooftop to rooftop before flying into their roost. This is a fairly small London Plane tree in a very urban setting. There is little other vegetation visible from here; below the tree is an area of astro turf. Pied wagtails however have adapted to the conditions here, although it's not clear what the benefits of communal roosting are for them.

It seems that improved foraging the following day as they follow one another out of the roost may be one reason. Others have suggested that the birds like the warm microclimate in these urban roosts but this is a very mild year and still the birds come here in their hundreds. Avoiding predators seems like an unlikely reason; this evening at twenty past five a Sparrowhawk silently chased the wagtails as they started to alight in the roost tree. The hawk landed in the tree for a moment before flying after the wagtails again. The wagtails soon started to come back into the roost which is when this recording begins. 

Given the nature of the place, there are lots of sounds present. There are the bells being rung at Bath Abbey. There are the voices and footsteps of the young, the old, locals and tourists. There are four different sounds to listen out for. Firstly the sweet, rather liquid calls which can be heard throughout the recording. These typically form the bird's song but are given here in another territorial situation (finding a place in the roost). 

Secondly, listen for their aggressive, or annoyed call. This sounds like arcing electricity and is best heard a number of times within the first 16s and from 9:33.
 
The third sound to listen for is quite unusual. This is the sound of bill snapping which en masse sounds like static electricity being discharged. Another XC contributor, Anthony McGeehan, has suggested that this activity is to assert their rights to their position in the roost (see XC290106).  In my recording it is present throughout although perhaps best heard from 10:20 when other sounds are at a minimum. It seems to come and go in waves. My best guess that as the sound of an individual bill snap is not very variable, it may help the birds to space themselves out equally throughout the tree. There are other recordings on XC of this behaviour worth listening to by Manuel Grosselet at Nantes Airport (XC297867) and a mixed roost of White and Yellow Wagtails by Raoul Kima in Germany (XC384295).

The final sound to note is their usual and more familiar call, "chis-ick", for example at 0:38.

rmk: Parte 4 de 4. La lavandera blanca es una especie invernante en esta zona de España, llegando aquí en gran número desde todos los puntos de Europa. Por la noche se reúnen en grandes dormideros comunales situados en grandes árboles preferiblemente en ciudad y cerca de carreteras con gran tráfico, pues allí la temperatura es más alta y el número de depredadores menor. Por el día forrajean en grupos laxos en cualquier zona descubierta de parques, jardines, pastizales ralos y aledaños de marisma. En este songscape de lavandera blanca podemos oír grupos de la especie forrajeando en una de sus zonas favoritas, un pastizal pelado cerca de un humedal. Junto a ellas se oyen otras especies de fondo. La reserva es a la vez paraje protegido, lugar de explotación de ganado vacuno extensivo y coto de caza. No sólo sus usos son heterogéneos, también lo son sus ecosistemas: hay una laguna temporal irrigada por el arroyo majaberraque, una zona de pastizal abierto, un bosque de acebuches adehesados y un pinar con árboles de gran envergadura. El suelo está muy desprovisto de vegetación por la gran carga ganadera de la zona, pero ésto es fundamental para algunas especies que requieren áreas muy áridas como Anthus Campestris, la bisbita campestre u Oenanthe Oennanthe, la collalba gris. Con todo es necesaria algo de regeneración vegetal y se han establecido pequeños cercaditos inaccesibles a las vacas para que en ellos crezcan acebuches nuevos y algo de hierba y matorral.

rmk:
Around 200 Pied Wagtails leaving their roost tree at dawn. Like the evening recording I made (XC526047), you can hear the various sounds the birds make in their communal roost. The track opens with bill snapping and their most common roost call which is a liquid slur and perhaps more well known as part of their song.  There are also the electric sounding aggressive calls, heard best at 2:49.

The wagtails leave the tree in groups. The first group leaves shortly after 22:25. Further groups leave after 24:00 and 25:40 with the main part of the flock leaving at 26:15. Note how after the initial groups leave the remaining birds go quiet for a few seconds. 

This is a challenging environment to make a sound recording, even at this time in the morning. There are various sounds of deliveries being made and you will also hear a security guard jingling his keys. It is therefore quite heavily edited: there was a loud air conditioning unit running and some wind noise which I have tried to remove. I have also reduced some sounds of me moving with varying success. Recording made with an Olympus LS-12 utilising the built in microphones.
